First, draw a sketch. We can label the \(H\) axis by adding integer multiples of 100 to 450. We know to shade the between \(350\) and \(540\) because those values satisfy the condition \(350 < X < 540\).


We calculate the \(z\) values of the boundaries. Left boundary: \[\begin{aligned} z_1 &= \frac{x_1-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{350-450}{100} \\\\ &= -1 \end{aligned}\]

Right boundary:

\[\begin{aligned} z_2 &= \frac{x_2-\mu}{\sigma} \\\\ &= \frac{540-450}{100} \\\\ &= 0.9 \end{aligned}\]

We rephrase our problem into a standard normal probability problem:

\[P\left(350 < X < 540\right) ~=~ P(-1<Z<0.9)\]

So, we just need to evaluate \(P(-1<Z<0.9)\).

From here we have a formula that lets us use the \(z\) table. (We practiced this part before.) \[\begin{aligned} P(z_1 < Z < z_2) &= P(Z<z_2) - P(Z<z1) \\ P(-1<Z<0.9) &= P(Z<0.9)-P(Z<-1)\\ &= 0.8159-0.1587 \\ &= 0.6572 \end{aligned}\]
